-- ============================================================================
-- COLUMBIA
-- ============================================================================
UPDATE countries SET country_brief = $$
Columbia is the world's preeminent power — a federal democracy with a GDP of 280 coins, the largest military on earth (67 units across four continents), and a nuclear arsenal rivaled only by Sarmatia. It leads the Western Treaty alliance, holds a permanent veto on the Council, and chairs the Seven. Its currency underpins global trade. Its semiconductor supply chain runs through Formosa, where a single company fabricates 65% of the advanced chips Columbia's economy and military depend on. For thirty years, no nation could challenge this dominance. That era is ending.

At simulation start, Columbia is fighting a war in Persia (Operation Epic Fury), sustaining a proxy conflict in Ruthenia, deterring Cathay in the Pacific, and waging a trade war whose legal foundations have been struck down by its own courts. President Dealer — age 80, approval at 38%, term-limited — launched the Persia campaign without legislative authorization. Two carrier strike groups and 10 military units are locked in the Middle East theater. Gas prices are surging. The first-ever trillion-coin defense budget strains a fiscal position already hemorrhaging 12 coins per round in trade deficit, with debt service at 5 coins and 30% of GDP locked into untouchable social spending. There is no strategic reserve. Any new crisis — a Cathay move on Formosa, a Choson provocation, a Sarmatia escalation — would require pulling forces from an existing commitment.

The succession race defines Columbia's internal politics. Vice President Volt and Secretary of State Anchor are already positioning for the presidential election at Round 5. Volt represents isolationist conservatism; Anchor represents hawkish interventionism with the Caribe regime change as his personal trophy. Their competing agendas mean Dealer's orders risk being slow-walked by subordinates calculating their own futures. Tribune leads the congressional opposition with the power to flip the legislature at Round 2 mid-terms. Challenger campaigns from outside, offering every foreign leader an alternative future. Shadow controls what intelligence Dealer sees. Shield manages an overstretched military with a philosophy that concerns career officers.

Every other country's strategy depends on what Columbia does. But Columbia itself cannot agree on what to do — because its president is chasing legacy, its successors are chasing power, its opposition is chasing the presidency, and the world will not wait for any of them to decide. Columbia's overstretch is not a temporary condition. It is the structural reality of a hegemon whose commitments have outgrown its capacity and political will — the classic precondition of the Thucydides Trap.
$$ WHERE id = 'columbia' AND sim_run_id = '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';

