-- CATHAY
-- ============================================================================
UPDATE countries SET country_brief = $$
Cathay is the rising pole of the Thucydides Trap — the world's second-largest economy (190 coins GDP), its largest manufacturer, its fastest-growing nuclear power, and the only nation with the structural trajectory to displace Columbia as global hegemon. Chairman Helmsman holds more personal power than any leader in Cathay's modern history: he has abolished term limits, purged over 100 senior military officers, and concentrated party, state, and military authority under singular control. There is no successor. There is no alternative center of power. There is only the Chairman and his vision of national rejuvenation — a vision that requires, before it can be declared complete, the resolution of the Formosa question.

The military paradox defines Cathay's position. The People's Liberation Army fields the world's largest navy by hull count, a nuclear arsenal expanding from 600 warheads toward 1,500, and a missile force that can hold Columbia's Pacific bases at risk. Naval production outpaces all Western navies combined. But five of seven Central Military Commission members have been purged. Marshal Rampart — the replacement — has no operational command experience. For the first two rounds, any complex military operation carries a 20% chance of implementation failure. The military is simultaneously more powerful and less competent than it has ever been.

Cathay's economy is a war machine running on export adrenaline while its domestic engine sputters. A record 12-coin trade surplus masks a property sector that has lost half its value, deflation persisting for a third year, youth unemployment near 18%, and a population declining for the fourth consecutive year. The technology race adds urgency: domestic AI chip production is advancing (SMIC at 7nm, DeepSeek V4 competitive with frontier models), but Cathay remains a decade behind in advanced lithography. Rare earth dominance — 90% of global refining — is the strongest leverage card. If Columbia reaches AI Level 4 first, the technological advantage may become permanent.

Behind the unified facade, five forces pull in different directions. Helmsman demands Formosa. Rampart cannot guarantee military success. Premier Abacus sees economic data showing confrontation leads to catastrophe. Circuit knows war would destroy the supply chains his tech empire depends on. Elder Sage waits — knowing that if the Chairman overreaches, the party's survival instinct will produce a correction. The disagreements are never public. They manifest as biased briefings, slow-walked orders, and selective information. The outside world can only guess. The window for action on Formosa may be opening — or it may already be closing. That uncertainty is the Trap.
$$ WHERE id = 'cathay' AND sim_run_id = '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';

