-- GALLIA
-- ============================================================================
UPDATE countries SET country_brief = $$
Gallia is Europe's most ambitious and most domestically constrained power — a nuclear-armed democracy with a GDP of 34 coins, a permanent Council veto, the continent's only independent carrier strike group, and a president whose approval rating sits between 11% and 16%. President Lumiere governs without a parliamentary majority, his domestic agenda paralyzed, but the constitutional prerogatives of the presidency give him near-unchallenged authority over defense and foreign affairs — and he is using every drop of it.

The forward deterrence speech represents the most significant shift in Gallia's nuclear doctrine in decades. Gallia will increase its warhead stockpile beyond the long-maintained ceiling of approximately 300 for the first time since 1992. The new doctrine extends a consultative nuclear umbrella to eight allied nations, including Teutonia, Freeland, and Albion. But Gallia retains sole decision-making authority — the button remains in its capital. This nuclear gambit is simultaneously a bid for European leadership, a hedge against Columbia's transactional unreliability, and a personal legacy project. It places Gallia at the center of every European defense conversation — but at the cost of deepening the Atlanticist-autonomist split that divides the continent.

Gallia deployed an unprecedented naval force to the Gulf independently of Columbia's Persia campaign — monitoring, not fighting, but demonstrating capacity for unilateral action that no other European power except Albion possesses. With 16 military units, a domestic defense industry (Dassault, Naval Group, Thales), and global bases from the Pacific to the Horn, Gallia can project power where others can only deliberate. The constraint is fiscal: 45% tax rate, 112% debt-to-GDP, and a social spending floor of 35% that is politically untouchable.

The player who runs Lumiere holds the only independent nuclear deterrent in the Ereb Union, the only Council veto among EU members, the most deployable military on the continent, and the most ambitious vision for European strategic autonomy. The tension with Freeland (which sees autonomy as weakening the Western Treaty) and with Teutonia (which prioritizes trade preservation over defense ambition) is the fault line that defines European politics. Gallia's grandest ambitions rest on the narrowest political foundations — a president with everything except domestic support.
$$ WHERE id = 'gallia' AND sim_run_id = '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';

