-- PONTE
-- ============================================================================
UPDATE countries SET country_brief = $$
Ponte is Europe's most consequential swing vote and its most financially vulnerable major power — a democracy with 22 coins GDP, 137.9% debt-to-GDP ratio, and 8 coins per round consumed by debt service alone. That fiscal reality means virtually no discretionary spending exists. Every policy choice is a fiscal choice, and whoever offers financial relief — Ereb Union recovery funds, Cathay investment, sanctions waivers — has leverage over Ponte's alignment. The third-largest EU economy and a G7 member, Ponte punches above its economic weight through sheer institutional position: it can veto any EU decision requiring unanimity, from sanctions on Sarmatia to Ruthenia's accession to trade restrictions on Cathay.

The governing coalition is fractious. Two of three coalition parties publicly question continued support for Ruthenia and sanctions on Sarmatia. One coalition leader has been accused of receiving Sarmatia funds and openly criticizes sanctions as harmful to domestic businesses. The March 2026 referendum defeat — 54% to 46% against the government's flagship judicial reform — weakened the prime minister's domestic mandate and emboldened coalition dissent. Ponte's chronic political instability (68 governments since 1946) means collapse is always a possibility, and a new government might be more Sarmatia-friendly, more Cathay-curious, and more willing to use the EU veto as a weapon.

Ponte is Columbia's favorite European partner — the only EU leader invited to the Dealer's inauguration, bonded by shared ideology and personal chemistry. This relationship makes Ponte the bridge between Columbia and the Ereb Union, trusted where others are despised. But it also makes Ponte the potential crack in European unity. When Ponte calls for Europe to "reach out to Sarmatia over peace," it carries weight that smaller dissenters never could, because Ponte is a founding EU member, a G7 economy, and a Western Treaty ally with a real military — 4 ground units, 2 naval, 2 tactical air, including a carrier.

Ponte's defection from the sanctions consensus would not just embarrass the EU. It would shatter it. That is why every diplomatic deal in Europe must account for whether Ponte will sign — and what Ponte wants in return.
$$ WHERE id = 'ponte' AND sim_run_id = '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';

