-- FREELAND
-- ============================================================================
UPDATE countries SET country_brief = $$
Freeland is the Western Treaty's most committed conventional military power and Europe's security conscience — a frontline democracy with 9 coins GDP, 4.8% of GDP allocated to defense (the highest ratio in the alliance), and a 200-billion-zloty military budget that shames every partner on the continent. This is not posturing. Freeland borders Sarmatia's exclave and the Ruthenia conflict zone. Eighty percent of all military aid to Ruthenia has transited Freeland territory through the logistics hub in its eastern city. For this country, the war next door is not an abstraction — it is the confirmation of everything Freeland warned about for decades while others built gas pipelines to Sarmatia.

The military buildup is real and accelerating: 5 ground units (with K2 tanks from joint production ventures), 2 tactical air units (F-35 procurement underway), 1 naval unit in the Baltic, and 1 air defense battery. Production capacity is expanding through defense industry partnerships. Columbia forward-deployed troops are hosted on Freeland soil. The goal of 5% GDP defense spending — years ahead of the alliance's 2035 target — is being achieved on the fastest-growing economy in Europe (3.7% GDP growth).

Freeland's strategic dilemma: it wants maximum Western Treaty commitment AND maximum Ereb Union solidarity, but these sometimes conflict. When Gallia pushes strategic autonomy, Freeland hears "weakening the alliance we depend on for survival." When Teutonia prioritizes Cathay trade, Freeland sees dangerous appeasement. When Columbia demands 5% spending, Freeland already exceeds it — giving moral authority to shame those who do not. The relationship with Ruthenia is the deepest bond: neighbor, weapons transit corridor, refugee host, and existential solidarity forged by shared understanding of the Sarmatia threat.

Domestically, Sentinel governs with a stable pro-EU coalition but faces an opposition president who can veto legislation and EU defense loans, creating friction on specific policies without undermining the broad security consensus. On defense and Ruthenia, there is near-unanimity across the political spectrum. Freeland speaks with the authority of a nation that lives next to the threat everyone else debates abstractly — the smallest economy among major European powers, but the largest military commitment.
