-- ALBION
-- ============================================================================
UPDATE countries SET country_brief = $$
Albion is Europe's second-largest military power, a nuclear state, a permanent Council member with veto power, and a core member of the Five Eyes intelligence alliance — all wielded from outside the Ereb Union. With 33 coins GDP, the strongest navy in Europe (4 naval units including 2 aircraft carriers), 2 strategic missile units (Trident submarines on continuous patrol with approximately 225 warheads), and global bases from Cyprus to the Falklands, Albion possesses capabilities no other European nation can match. The structural problem is unique: Albion participates in Western Treaty military coordination but cannot vote on any EU decision affecting sanctions, trade, enlargement, or defense spending. Influence without a seat at the table where economic decisions happen.

Five Eyes is the unique trading chip. Columbia shares intelligence with Albion that it does not share with EU allies through alliance channels. This means Albion can selectively share intelligence with European partners — Gallia, Teutonia, Freeland — to buy influence and cooperation. The intelligence asymmetry is real and consequential: Albion knows things about Sarmatia's military posture, Cathay's intentions, and Columbia's internal deliberations that other European nations can only access through Albion's willingness to share.

Prime Minister Mariner has seized diplomatic initiative on Ruthenia — hosting virtual meetings of Western leaders, initiating a "coalition of the willing" for peace deal implementation, and offering Albion troops as part of a ceasefire monitoring force. This activism is rebuilding European partnerships damaged by the exit from the EU and demonstrating post-departure relevance through military capability and diplomatic leadership. The Strategic Defence Review accepted recommendations for nuclear modernization (including a second delivery system beyond the submarine deterrent), a reserve corps of two army divisions, and enhanced maritime contribution to the North Atlantic. Defense spending targets 2.5% of GDP by 2027 and 3% by end of parliament.

Albion's constraint is fiscal: 100% debt-to-GDP, 3 coins per round in debt service, 30% social spending baseline, and persistent trade deficits. The nuclear deterrent alone absorbs 25% of the defense budget. The economy is services-dominated with the financial center as the crown jewel, but post-departure trade friction with the EU persists. Mariner must project global ambition on a national budget that is already stretched — the eternal Albion challenge of a medium-sized economy with great-power aspirations.
