-- SARMATIA
-- ============================================================================
UPDATE countries SET country_brief = $$
Sarmatia is a nuclear superpower fighting a grinding land war in eastern Ruthenia, under the heaviest Western sanctions regime in history, led by a 73-year-old president who has concentrated more personal power than any leader since the Soviet era — and who has no successor. The war, now in its fifth year, defines everything. Launched as a three-day special operation to decapitate a neighboring government, it became the largest conventional war in Europe since 1945. Sarmatia occupies approximately 20% of Ruthenia's territory across four annexed oblasts — a claim it cannot fully enforce militarily. Thirteen of eighteen ground units are committed to the theater. Casualties may exceed one million. North Korean troops fight alongside Sarmatian forces.

The economy has proven more resilient than Western analysts predicted — and more fragile than the leadership admits. GDP of 20 coins, growth collapsed to 1%, defense spending consuming 40% of the federal budget. Oil revenues — the lifeblood — are declining as sanctions bite and Cathay demands ever-deeper discounts. The Central Bank rate sits at 15%, inflation is being muscled down from double digits. The National Wealth Fund is depleted. Sanctions have disconnected major banks from the global financial system, restricted technology imports, and frozen approximately 300 billion in foreign reserves. The economy works for now. It will not work indefinitely.

Pathfinder's control is absolute in formal terms but depends on information filtered by subordinates. Ironhand controls the military and co-authorizes nuclear launch — the one thing Pathfinder cannot do without him. Compass manages an economy whose real numbers (stagnation, depleting reserves, collapsing regional budgets) are worse than what reaches the president, and holds 3 personal coins frozen abroad by sanctions — a direct financial incentive for peace that may diverge from Pathfinder's territorial ambitions. The partnership with Cathay provides economic survival but at the cost of becoming the junior partner in an increasingly asymmetric relationship. The nuclear arsenal — the world's largest at approximately 5,500 warheads, now unconstrained by any treaty — remains the ultimate guarantor of sovereignty.

Sarmatia must decide whether to consolidate, escalate, or negotiate. Pathfinder's legacy demands something he can call victory. The general wants either a real military result or an honest admission that one is impossible. The oligarch wants the war over and sanctions lifted. The war economy drain (2 extra coins per round) and cumulative war tiredness (currently 4, rising each round) create a structural clock: time is not on Sarmatia's side, even if the front line holds.
$$ WHERE id = 'sarmatia' AND sim_run_id = '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';

-- ============================================================================
-- RUTHENIA
-- ============================================================================
UPDATE countries SET country_brief = $$
Ruthenia is the human cost of the Thucydides Trap made visible — a wartime democracy of 2.2 coins GDP fighting for survival against a nuclear superpower, sustained by Western aid that could be cut at any moment, and governed by three leaders who represent three genuinely different responses to an impossible situation. The war, now in its fifth year, has destroyed 14% of all housing, pushed public debt beyond 123% of GDP, and created reconstruction needs of 588 billion over the next decade — three times the country's annual output. The economy functions because the West keeps it alive: European aid rose 67% as Columbia's aid collapsed by 99%.

Seven of ten ground units hold the front line against thirteen Sarmatian ground units — a 1:1.85 disadvantage partially offset by defensive positions, Western weapons (F-16s, HIMARS, Storm Shadow), and higher motivation. The navy was destroyed in 2022 but innovative drone warfare forced Sarmatia's Black Sea Fleet from its base. Ruthenia has zero strategic missiles — it surrendered its nuclear arsenal under the Budapest Memorandum in exchange for security guarantees that proved worthless. That foundational betrayal shapes every negotiation: promises are paper, only capabilities are real. Air defense is the most critical scarce resource — a single unit of Western-supplied Patriot and NASAMS systems must protect the capital and critical infrastructure from relentless missile and drone barrages.

The three-way political competition defines Ruthenia's direction. President Beacon — wartime hero, approval falling to 52%, first-round polling at 22.6% — holds executive power under martial law but faces eroding legitimacy after a corruption scandal. General Bulwark commands the army's loyalty and would win a runoff 64-36 — his restraint in refusing to seize power is both principled and strategic. Former president Broker has neither military credibility nor executive power but has European connections and the argument that negotiated peace, not endless war, saves the country. The election (Round 3 or 4) will be triggered by external pressure, stability collapse, or candidate initiative.

Columbia's 28-point peace plan would cede Crimea, Donetsk, and Luhansk to Sarmatia and constitutionally bar Ruthenia from the Western Treaty. Eighty-two percent of citizens find territorial cession unacceptable. But 63% say they are ready to continue fighting — a number that was 80% in 2022 and is falling. EU membership — the one guarantee Ruthenia trusts — is blocked by Ponte. The gap between what the population will accept and what the world is offering is the political crisis. Aid dependency (2 coins per round from the Western coalition) means economic survival is not guaranteed — if aid drops below 1 coin, stability collapses immediately.
$$ WHERE id = 'ruthenia' AND sim_run_id = '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001';

