Cathay provides approximately 90% of Choson's trade and energy — the economic lifeline. But Cathay is embarrassed by Choson's provocations and fears nuclear proliferation destabilizing the region. Cathay tolerates Choson because the alternative — regime collapse and Columbia troops on Cathay's border — is worse. Choson exploits this calculation ruthlessly. The March 2026 missile barrage — 10 simultaneous launches — demonstrated provocative capability at unprecedented scale. Seoul, with 25 million people, sits 35 miles from the DMZ under thousands of artillery pieces. The threat is not nuclear — it is conventional. Choson can devastate the Hanguk capital in hours without crossing the nuclear threshold.

Choson's power is crisis on demand. A nuclear test, an ICBM launch over Yamato, an artillery barrage near the DMZ — any of these can be triggered at any time, forcing Columbia, Hanguk, Yamato, and Cathay to divert attention and resources from whatever they were doing. During the Persia war, when Columbia is maximally overstretched, this capability is at its most dangerous. The regime spends 25-30% of GDP on the military. The population endures conditions that would cause revolution anywhere else, but the totalitarian surveillance apparatus prevents organized dissent. There is no succession mechanism. If the leader is incapacitated, the system has no plan.
