-- ============================================================================
-- FORMOSA
-- ============================================================================
UPDATE countries SET country_brief = $$
Formosa is the most dangerous tripwire in the world — a functionally independent democracy of 24 million people that fabricates the majority of the planet's advanced semiconductors, claimed as sovereign territory by the simulation's rising great power, and defended by the declining hegemon under a policy of deliberate ambiguity. TSMC, Formosa's crown jewel, produces nearly one-third of all global computing power and the vast majority of cutting-edge chips below 7nm. Every AI model trained, every advanced weapons system built, every smartphone sold depends on facilities concentrated on this single island. The "silicon shield" is Formosa's greatest strategic asset — the world cannot afford to let these fabs be destroyed or captured.

But the shield is eroding. Columbia's CHIPS Act fabs, Yamato's Rapidus project, and Cathay's own semiconductor push all reduce the concentration that makes Formosa indispensable. Every fab built abroad makes the island marginally more expendable. At simulation start, Columbia's Formosa semiconductor dependency stands at 0.65 — still critically high, but falling. Cathay's is 0.25 and declining faster. The window in which Formosa's economic value protects it from military action is closing.

Cathay's military pressure is relentless. Record air incursions, major exercises, and the largest military buildup ever pointed at a single target. A selective quarantine could cripple Formosa's semiconductor supply chain within weeks — the island depends on imported natural gas, chemicals, and raw materials. Full invasion remains the nightmare scenario, but blockade or quarantine offers Cathay a gray-zone option harder for Columbia to counter with military force. Formosa's own military — 4 ground units, 2 naval, 3 tactical air, 2 air defense — is configured for asymmetric "porcupine" defense: delay the invasion fleet, make the island indigestible, and hold until Columbia arrives. Whether Columbia arrives is the question nobody can answer.

Internal gridlock compounds the vulnerability. The pro-sovereignty president proposed a landmark $40 billion special defense budget. The opposition-controlled legislature — sympathetic to cross-strait engagement — slashed it by 70% and launched impeachment proceedings. Formosa cannot agree on how seriously to take its own defense. The economy (8 coins GDP, 3% growth, massive trade surplus of 4 coins) is healthy but entirely dependent on continued semiconductor demand and continued peace. A 55% political support level masks a genuine societal split between those who would resist and those who would accommodate Cathay. Columbia watches with alarm as its protectorate fails to implement the defense strategy it considers essential.
